attributes.name: required
attributes.description: The Boolean required attribute, if present, indicates that the user must specify a value for the input before the owning form can be submitted.

attributes.name: multiple
attributes.description: The Boolean multiple attribute, if set, means the form control accepts one or more values. The attribute is valid for the email and file input types and the <select>. The manner by which the user opts for multiple values depends on the form control.

attributes.name: size
attributes.description: The size attribute defines the width of the <input> and the height of the <select> element. For an input element, it defines the number of characters that the user agent allows the user to see when editing the value. For a select element, it defines the number of options that should be shown to the user. This must be a valid non-negative integer greater than zero.

attributes.name: form
attributes.description: The form HTML attribute associates a form-associated element with a <form> element within the same document. This attribute applies to the <button>, <fieldset>, <input>, <object>, <output>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

attributes.name: name
attributes.description: The name property of the HTMLSelectElement interface indicates the name of the <select> element. It reflects the element's name attribute.

events.name: change
events.description: The change event is fired for <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements when the user modifies the element's value. Unlike the input event, the change event is not necessarily fired for each alteration to an element's value.

attributes.name: name
attributes.description: The name property of the HTMLSlotElement interface returns or sets the slot name. A slot is a placeholder inside a web component that users can fill with their own markup.

events.name: slotchange
events.description: The slotchange event is fired on an HTMLSlotElement instance (<slot> element) when the node(s) contained in that slot change.

attributes.name: height
attributes.description: The height property of the HTMLSourceElement interface is a non-negative number indicating the height of the image resource in CSS pixels.

attributes.name: media
attributes.description: The media property of the HTMLSourceElement interface is a string representing the intended destination medium for the resource. The value is a media query, which is a comma separated list of media-types, media-features, and logical operators.

attributes.name: sizes
attributes.description: The sizes property of the HTMLSourceElement interface is a string representing a list of one or more sizes, representing sizes between breakpoints, to which the resource applies.

attributes.name: src
attributes.description: The src property of the HTMLSourceElement interface is a string indicating the URL of a media resource to use as the source for the element.

attributes.name: srcset
attributes.description: The srcset property of the HTMLSourceElement interface is a string containing a comma-separated list of candidate images.

attributes.name: type
attributes.description: The type property of the HTMLSourceElement interface is a string representing the MIME type of the media resource.

attributes.name: width
attributes.description: The width property of the HTMLSourceElement interface is a non-negative number indicating the width of the image resource in CSS pixels.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event is fired on an element when a resource failed to load, or can't be used. For example, if a script has an execution error or an image can't be found or is invalid.

attributes.name: type
attributes.description: The HTMLStyleElement.type property returns the type of the current style. The value mirrors the HTML <style> element's type attribute.

attributes.name: blocking
attributes.description: The read-only blocking property of the HTMLStyleElement returns a live DOMTokenList object containing the operations that should be blocked on the fetching of an external resource. It reflects the <style> element's blocking content attribute.

attributes.name: media
attributes.description: The HTMLStyleElement.media property specifies the intended destination medium for style information.

attributes.name: align
attributes.description: The align property of the HTMLTableCaptionElement interface is a string indicating how to horizontally align text in the <caption> table element.

attributes.name: scope
attributes.description: The scope property of the HTMLTableCellElement interface indicates the scope of a <th> cell.

attributes.name: abbr
attributes.description: The abbr property of the HTMLTableCellElement interface indicates an abbreviation associated with the cell. If the cell does not represent a header cell <th>, it is ignored.

attributes.name: align
attributes.description: The align property of the HTMLTableCellElement interface is a string indicating how to horizontally align text in the <th> or <td> table cell.

attributes.name: headers
attributes.description: The headers property of the HTMLTableCellElement interface contains a list of IDs of <th> elements that are headers for this specific cell.

attributes.name: align
attributes.description: The align property of the HTMLTableColElement interface is a string indicating how to horizontally align text in a table <col> column element.

attributes.name: span
attributes.description: The span property of the HTMLTableColElement interface represents the number of columns this <col> or <colgroup> must span; this lets the column occupy space across multiple columns of the table. It reflects the span attribute.

attributes.name: border
attributes.description: The HTMLTableElement.border property represents the border width of the <table> element.

attributes.name: align
attributes.description: The HTMLTableElement.align property represents the alignment of the table.

attributes.name: frame
attributes.description: The HTMLTableElement interface's frame property is a string that indicates which of the table's exterior borders should be drawn.

attributes.name: rules
attributes.description: The HTMLTableElement.rules property indicates which cell borders to render in the table.

attributes.name: summary
attributes.description: The HTMLTableElement.summary property represents the table description.

attributes.name: width
attributes.description: The HTMLTableElement.width property represents the desired width of the table.

attributes.name: align
attributes.description: The align property of the HTMLTableRowElement interface is a string indicating how to horizontally align text in the <tr> table row. Individual cells can override it.

attributes.name: align
attributes.description: The align property of the HTMLTableSectionElement interface is a string indicating how to horizontally align text in a <thead>, <tbody> or <tfoot> table section. Individual rows and cells can override it.

attributes.name: autocomplete
attributes.description: The HTML autocomplete attribute lets web developers specify what if any permission the user agent has to provide automated assistance in filling out form field values, as well as guidance to the browser as to the type of information expected in the field.

attributes.name: disabled
attributes.description: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.

attributes.name: maxlength
attributes.description: The maxlength attribute defines the maximum string length that the user can enter into an <input> or <textarea>. The attribute must have an integer value of 0 or higher.

attributes.name: placeholder
attributes.description: The placeholder attribute defines the text displayed in a form control when the control has no value. The placeholder text should provide a brief hint to the user as to the expected type of data that should be entered into the control.

attributes.name: readonly
attributes.description: The Boolean readonly attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, meaning the user can not edit the control.

attributes.name: required
attributes.description: The Boolean required attribute, if present, indicates that the user must specify a value for the input before the owning form can be submitted.

attributes.name: form
attributes.description: The form HTML attribute associates a form-associated element with a <form> element within the same document. This attribute applies to the <button>, <fieldset>, <input>, <object>, <output>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

attributes.name: minlength
attributes.description: The minlength attribute defines the minimum string length that the user can enter into an <input> or <textarea>. The attribute must have an integer value of 0 or higher.

attributes.name: dirname
attributes.description: The dirname attribute can be used on the <textarea> element and several <input> types and describes the directionality of the element's text content during form submission. The browser uses this attribute's value to determine whether text the user has entered is left-to-right or right-to-left oriented. When used, the element's text directionality value is included in form submission data along with the dirname attribute's value as the name of the field.

attributes.name: wrap
attributes.description: The wrap property of the HTMLTextAreaElement interface indicates how the control should wrap the value for form submission. It reflects the <textarea> element's wrap attribute. Note that the "hard" value only has an effect when the cols attribute is also set.

attributes.name: cols
attributes.description: The cols property of the HTMLTextAreaElement interface is a positive integer representing the visible width of the multi-line text control, in average character widths. It reflects the <textarea> element's cols attribute.

attributes.name: name
attributes.description: The name property of the HTMLTextAreaElement interface indicates the name of the <textarea> element. It reflects the element's name attribute.

attributes.name: rows
attributes.description: The rows property of the HTMLTextAreaElement interface is a positive integer representing the visible text lines of the text control. It reflects the <textarea> element's rows attribute.

events.name: select
events.description: The select event fires when some text has been selected.

attributes.name: default
attributes.description: The default property of the HTMLTrackElement interface represents whether the track will be enabled if the user's preferences do not indicate that another track would be more appropriate. It reflects the <track> element's boolean default attribute, returning true if present and false otherwise.

attributes.name: kind
attributes.description: The kind property of the HTMLTrackElement interface represents the type of track, or how the text track is meant to be used. It reflects the <track> element's enumerated kind attribute.

attributes.name: label
attributes.description: The label property of the HTMLTrackElement represents the user-readable title displayed when listing subtitle, caption, and audio descriptions for a track. It reflects the <track> element's label attribute.

attributes.name: src
attributes.description: The src property of the HTMLTrackElement interface reflects the value of the <track> element's src attribute, which indicates the URL of the text track's data.

attributes.name: srclang
attributes.description: The srclang property of the HTMLTrackElement interface reflects the value of the <track> element's srclang attribute or the empty string if not defined.

events.description: The error event is fired on an element when a resource failed to load, or can't be used. For example, if a script has an execution error or an image can't be found or is invalid.

events.name: cuechange
events.description: The cuechange event fires when a TextTrack has changed the currently displaying cues. The event is fired on both the TextTrack and the HTMLTrackElement in which it's being presented, if any.

attributes.name: compact

attributes.name: poster
attributes.description: The poster property of the HTMLVideoElement interface is a string that reflects the URL for an image to be shown while no video data is available. If the property does not represent a valid URL, no poster frame will be shown.

attributes.name: height
attributes.description: The height property of the HTMLVideoElement interface returns an integer that reflects the height attribute of the <video> element, specifying the displayed height of the resource in CSS pixels.

attributes.name: width
attributes.description: The width property of the HTMLVideoElement interface returns an integer that reflects the width attribute of the <video> element, specifying the displayed width of the resource in CSS pixels.

events.name: enterpictureinpicture
events.description: The enterpictureinpicture event is fired when the HTMLVideoElement enters picture-in-picture mode successfully.

events.name: leavepictureinpicture
events.description: The leavepictureinpicture event is fired when the HTMLVideoElement leaves picture-in-picture mode successfully.

events.name: versionchange
events.description: The versionchange event is fired when a database structure change (upgradeneeded event send on an IDBOpenDBRequest or IDBFactory.deleteDatabase) was requested elsewhere (most probably in another window/tab on the same computer).

events.name: close
events.description: The close event is fired on IDBDatabase when the database connection is unexpectedly closed. This could happen, for example, if the underlying storage is removed or if the user clears the database in the browser's history preferences.

events.name: upgradeneeded
events.description: The upgradeneeded event is fired when an attempt was made to open a database with a version number higher than its current version.

events.name: success
events.description: The success event is fired when an IDBRequest succeeds. In the success event handler, you can access the result of the request, as well as place more requests to the same transaction.

events.name: blocked
events.description: The blocked handler is executed when an open connection to a database is blocking a versionchange transaction on the same database.

events.name: success
events.description: The success event is fired when an IDBRequest succeeds. In the success event handler, you can access the result of the request, as well as place more requests to the same transaction.

events.name: error
events.description: The error handler is executed when an error caused a request to fail. In the error event handler, you can access the error of the request, as well as place more requests to the same transaction.

events.name: complete
events.description: The complete event of the IndexedDB API is fired when the transaction has successfully committed, which is either after you explicit call IDBTransaction.commit() or when all requests have been successfully completed, and after handling their results, no new requests have been placed. See IDBTransaction for more information.

events.name: abort
events.description: The abort event is fired when an IndexedDB transaction is aborted.

events.name: change
events.description: The change event of the IdleDetector interface fires when the value of userState or screenState has changed.

events.name: devicechange
events.description: The devicechange event is sent to a MediaDevices instance whenever a media device such as a camera, microphone, or speaker is connected to or removed from the system.

events.name: keystatuseschange
events.description: The keystatuseschange event of the MediaKeySession API fires when there has been a change in the keys or their statuses within a session.

events.name: message
events.description: The message event of the MediaKeySession interface fires when a message is generated by the content decryption module.

events.name: change
events.description: The change event of the MediaQueryList interface fires when the status of media query support changes.

events.name: dataavailable
events.description: The dataavailable event of the MediaRecorder interface is fired when the MediaRecorder delivers media data to your application for its use. The data is provided in a Blob object that contains the data. This occurs in four situations:

events.name: stop
events.description: The stop event of the MediaRecorder interface is fired when MediaRecorder.stop() is called, or when the media stream being captured ends. In each case, the stop event is preceded by a dataavailable event, making the Blob captured up to that point available for you to use in your application.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event of the MediaRecorder interface is fired when an error occurs: for example because recording wasn't allowed or was attempted using an unsupported codec.

events.name: start
events.description: The start event of the MediaRecorder interface is fired when MediaRecorder.start() is called. At this point, the data starts being gathered into a Blob.

events.name: pause
events.description: The pause event of the MediaRecorder interface is fired when MediaRecorder.pause() is called.

events.name: resume
events.description: The resume event of the MediaRecorder interface is fired when MediaRecorder.resume() is called.

events.name: sourceclose
events.description: The sourceclose event is fired when a MediaSource object's readyState changes to "closed". This indicates that the MediaSource has been detached from the media element.

events.name: sourceended
events.description: The sourceended event is fired when a MediaSource object's readyState changes to "ended". This indicates that the application has finished sending data to the MediaSource. When an application has finished appending all media data to the SourceBuffer objects associated with a MediaSource, it calls the MediaSource.endOfStream() method on the MediaSource. This causes the readyState to transition to "ended" and triggers the sourceended event.

events.name: sourceopen
events.description: The sourceopen event is fired when a MediaSource object's readyState changes to "open". This indicates that the MediaSource is ready to receive data from SourceBuffer objects. This can occur either when the MediaSource object is first attached to a media element or when the readyState changes from "ended" back to "open".

events.name: addtrack
events.description: The addtrack event is fired when a new MediaStreamTrack object has been added to a MediaStream.

events.name: removetrack
events.description: The removetrack event is fired when a new MediaStreamTrack object has been removed from a MediaStream.

events.name: ended
events.description: The ended event of the MediaStreamTrack interface is fired when playback or streaming has stopped because the end of the media was reached or because no further data is available.

events.name: mute
events.description: The mute event is sent to a MediaStreamTrack when the track's source is temporarily unable to provide media data.

events.name: unmute
events.description: The unmute event is sent to a MediaStreamTrack when the track's source is once again able to provide media data after a period of not being able to do so.

events.name: message
events.description: The message event is fired on a MessagePort object when a message arrives on that channel.

events.name: messageerror
events.description: The messageerror event is fired on a MessagePort object when it receives a message that can't be deserialized.

events.name: statechange
events.description: The statechange event of the MIDIAccess interface is fired when a new MIDI port is added or when an existing port changes state.

events.name: midimessage
events.description: The midimessage event of the Web MIDI API is fired when the MIDI port corresponding to this MIDIInput finishes receiving one or more MIDI messages. An instance of MIDIMessageEvent containing the message that was received is passed to the event handler.

events.name: statechange
events.description: The statechange event of the MIDIPort interface is fired when a port changes from open to closed, or closed to open.

events.name: navigate
events.description: The navigate event of the Navigation interface is fired when any type of navigation is initiated, allowing you to intercept as required.

events.name: currententrychange
events.description: The currententrychange event of the Navigation interface is fired when the Navigation.currentEntry has changed.

events.name: navigateerror
events.description: The navigateerror event of the Navigation interface is fired when a navigation fails.

events.name: navigatesuccess
events.description: The navigatesuccess event of the Navigation interface is fired when a successful navigation has finished.

events.name: dispose
events.description: The dispose event of the NavigationHistoryEntry interface is fired when the entry is no longer part of the history entry list.

events.name: reading
events.description: The reading event of the NDEFReader interface is fired whenever a new reading is available from compatible NFC devices (e.g., NFC tags supporting NDEF) when these devices are within the reader's magnetic induction field.

events.name: readingerror
events.description: The readingerror event of the NDEFReader interface is fired whenever an error occurs during reading of NFC tags, e.g., when tags leave the reader's magnetic induction field.

events.name: change
events.description: The change event of the NetworkInformation interface fires when connection information changes, and the event is received by the NetworkInformation object.

events.name: click
events.description: The click event of the Notification interface fires when the user clicks on displayed Notification.

events.name: show
events.description: The show event of the Notification interface fires when a Notification is displayed.

events.name: close
events.description: The close event of the Notification interface fires when a Notification is closed.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event of the Notification interface fires when something goes wrong with a Notification (in many cases an error preventing the notification from being displayed.)

events.name: complete
events.description: The complete event of the OfflineAudioContext interface is fired when the rendering of an offline audio context is complete.

events.name: contextlost
events.description: The contextlost event of the OffscreenCanvas interface is fired if the browser detects that the OffscreenCanvasRenderingContext2D context is lost. Contexts can be lost for several reasons, such as an associated GPU driver crashes, or the application runs out of memory, and so on.

events.name: contextrestored
events.description: The contextrestored event of the OffscreenCanvas interface is fired if the browser restores an OffscreenCanvasRenderingContext2D context that was previously lost.

events.name: paymentmethodchange
events.description: The paymentmethodchange event is delivered the Payment Request API to a PaymentRequest object when the user changes the payment method within a given payment handler.

events.name: shippingaddresschange
events.description: The shippingaddresschange event is sent to the PaymentRequest object when the user selects a shipping address or changes details of their shipping address.

events.name: shippingoptionchange
events.description: For payment requests that request shipping information, and for which shipping options are offered, the shippingoptionchange event is sent to the PaymentRequest whenever the user chooses a shipping option from the list of available options.

events.name: payerdetailchange
events.description: A payerdetailchange event is fired by the Payment Request API to a PaymentResponse object when the user makes changes to their personal information while filling out a payment request form. This can happen when the payer is retrying to submit its details after an error has been detected.

events.name: resourcetimingbufferfull
events.description: The resourcetimingbufferfull event is fired when the browser's resource timing buffer is full.

events.name: change
events.description: The change event of the PermissionStatus interface fires whenever the PermissionStatus.state property changes.

events.name: resize
events.description: The resize event fires when the floating video window has been resized.

events.name: connect
events.description: The connect event of the RemotePlayback interface fires when the user agent connects to the remote device.

events.name: connecting
events.description: The connecting event of the RemotePlayback interface fires when the user agent initiates remote playback.

events.name: disconnect
events.description: The disconnect event of the RemotePlayback interface fires when the user agent disconnects from the remote device.

events.name: message
events.description: The WebRTC message event is sent to the onmessage event handler on an RTCDataChannel object when a message has been received from the remote peer.

events.name: bufferedamountlow
events.description: A bufferedamountlow event is sent to an RTCDataChannel when the number of bytes currently in the outbound data transfer buffer (bufferedAmount) falls from above to below or equal the threshold specified in bufferedAmountLowThreshold.

events.name: close
events.description: The close event is sent to the onclose event handler on an RTCDataChannel instance when the data transport for the data channel has closed. Before any further data can be transferred using RTCDataChannel, a new 'RTCDataChannel' instance must be created.

events.name: closing
events.description: The closing event is sent to an RTCDataChannel just before the channel begins the process of shutting down its underlying data transport.

events.name: error
events.description: A WebRTC error event is sent to an RTCDataChannel object's onerror event handler when an error occurs on the data channel.

events.name: open
events.description: The WebRTC open event is sent to an RTCDataChannel object's onopen event handler when the underlying transport used to send and receive the data channel's messages is opened or reopened.

events.name: error
events.description: An RTCDtlsTransport receives an error event when a transport-level error occurs on the RTCPeerConnection.

events.name: tonechange
events.description: The tonechange event is sent to an RTCDTMFSender by the WebRTC API to indicate when DTMF tones previously queued for sending (by calling RTCDTMFSender.insertDTMF()) begin and end.

events.name: gatheringstatechange
events.description: A gatheringstatechange event is sent to an RTCIceTransport when its ICE candidate gathering state changes.

events.name: selectedcandidatepairchange
events.description: A selectedcandidatepairchange event is sent to an RTCIceTransport when the ICE agent selects a new pair of candidates that describe the endpoints of a viable connection.

events.name: statechange
events.description: A statechange event occurs when the RTCIceTransport changes state. The state can be used to determine how far through the process of examining, verifying, and selecting a valid candidate pair is prior to successfully connecting the two peers for WebRTC communications.

events.name: icecandidate
events.description: An icecandidate event is sent to an RTCPeerConnection when:

events.name: track
events.description: The track event is sent to the ontrack event handler on RTCPeerConnections after a new track has been added to an RTCRtpReceiver which is part of the connection.

events.name: connectionstatechange
events.description: The connectionstatechange event is sent to the onconnectionstatechange event handler on an RTCPeerConnection object after a new track has been added to an RTCRtpReceiver which is part of the connection. The new connection state can be found in connectionState, and is one of the string values: new, connecting, connected, disconnected, failed, or closed.

events.name: negotiationneeded
events.description: A negotiationneeded event is sent to the RTCPeerConnection when negotiation of the connection through the signaling channel is required. This occurs both during the initial setup of the connection as well as any time a change to the communication environment requires reconfiguring the connection.

events.name: iceconnectionstatechange
events.description: An iceconnectionstatechange event is sent to an RTCPeerConnection object each time the ICE connection state changes during the negotiation process. The new ICE connection state is available in the object's iceConnectionState property.

events.description: A datachannel event is sent to an RTCPeerConnection instance when an RTCDataChannel has been added to the connection, as a result of the remote peer calling RTCPeerConnection.createDataChannel().

events.name: icecandidateerror
events.description: The WebRTC API event icecandidateerror is sent to an RTCPeerConnection if an error occurs while performing ICE negotiations through a STUN or TURN server. The event object is of type RTCPeerConnectionIceErrorEvent, and contains information describing the error in some amount of detail.

events.name: icegatheringstatechange
events.description: The icegatheringstatechange event is sent to the onicegatheringstatechange event handler on an RTCPeerConnection when the state of the ICE candidate gathering process changes. This signifies that the value of the connection's iceGatheringState property has changed.

events.name: signalingstatechange
events.description: A signalingstatechange event is sent to an RTCPeerConnection to notify it that its signaling state, as indicated by the signalingState property, has changed.

events.name: statechange
events.description: A statechange event is sent to an RTCSctpTransport to provide notification when the RTCSctpTransport.state property has changed.

events.name: currentscreenchange
events.description: The currentscreenchange event of the ScreenDetails interface is fired when the ScreenDetails.currentScreen changes in one of the following ways:

events.name: screenschange
events.description: The screenschange event of the ScreenDetails interface is fired when the set of screens available to the system has changed: that is, a new screen has become available or an existing screen has become unavailable. This will be reflected in a change in the screens array.

events.name: change
events.description: The change event of the ScreenOrientation interface fires when the orientation of the screen has changed, for example when a user rotates their mobile phone.

events.name: audioprocess
events.description: The audioprocess event of the ScriptProcessorNode interface is fired when an input buffer of a script processor is ready to be processed.

events.name: activate
events.description: The activate event is fired when a sensor becomes activated. It means that it will start obtaining readings.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event is fired when an exception occurs on a sensor.

events.name: reading
events.description: The reading event is fired when a new reading is available on a sensor.

events.name: connect
events.description: The connect event of the SerialPort interface is fired when the port connects to the device.

events.name: disconnect
events.description: The disconnect event of the SerialPort interface is fired when the port disconnects from the device.

events.name: statechange
events.description: The statechange event fires anytime the ServiceWorker.state changes.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event fires whenever an error occurs in the service worker.

events.name: controllerchange
events.description: The controllerchange event of the ServiceWorkerContainer interface fires when the document's associated ServiceWorkerRegistration acquires a new active worker.

events.name: message
events.description: The message event is used in a page controlled by a service worker to receive messages from the service worker.

events.name: message

events.name: messageerror
events.description: The messageerror event is fired to the ServiceWorkerContainer when an incoming message sent to the associated worker can't be deserialized.

events.name: messageerror
events.description: The messageerror event is fired to the ServiceWorkerContainer when an incoming message sent to the associated worker can't be deserialized.

events.name: notificationclick
events.description: The notificationclick event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired to indicate that a system notification spawned by ServiceWorkerRegistration.showNotification() has been clicked.

events.name: fetch
events.description: The fetch event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired in the service worker's global scope when the main app thread makes a network request. It enables the service worker to intercept network requests and send customized responses (for example, from a local cache).

events.name: install
events.description: The install event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when a ServiceWorkerRegistration acquires a new ServiceWorkerRegistration.installing worker.

events.name: activate
events.description: The activate event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when a ServiceWorkerRegistration acquires a new ServiceWorkerRegistration.active worker.

events.name: message
events.description: The message event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface occurs when incoming messages are received. Controlled pages can use the ServiceWorker.postMessage() method to send messages to service workers. The service worker can optionally send a response back via the Client.postMessage(), corresponding to the controlled page.

events.name: push
events.description: The push event is sent to a service worker's global scope (represented by the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface) when the service worker has received a push message.

events.name: pushsubscriptionchange
events.description: The pushsubscriptionchange event is sent to the global scope of a ServiceWorker to indicate a change in push subscription that was triggered outside the application's control.

events.name: sync
events.description: The sync event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when the page (or worker) that registered the event with the SyncManager is running and as soon as network connectivity is available.

events.name: notificationclose
events.description: The notificationclose event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface fires when a user closes a displayed notification spawned by ServiceWorkerRegistration.showNotification().

events.name: backgroundfetchabort
events.description: The backgroundfetchabort event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when the user or the app itself cancels a background fetch operation.

events.name: backgroundfetchclick
events.description: The backgroundfetchclick event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when the user clicks on the UI that the browser provides to show the user the progress of the background fetch operation.

events.name: backgroundfetchfail
events.description: The backgroundfetchfail event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when a background fetch operation has failed: that is, when at least one network request in the fetch has failed to complete successfully.

events.name: backgroundfetchsuccess
events.description: The backgroundfetchsuccess event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when a background fetch operation has completed successfully: that is, when all network requests in the fetch have completed successfully.

events.name: canmakepayment
events.description: The canmakepayment event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired on a payment app's service worker to check whether it is ready to handle a payment. Specifically, it is fired when the merchant website calls the PaymentRequest() constructor.

events.name: contentdelete
events.description: The contentdelete event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when an item is removed from the indexed content via the user agent.

events.name: cookiechange
events.description: The cookiechange event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired when a cookie change occurs that matches the service worker's cookie change subscription list.

events.name: messageerror
events.description: The messageerror event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface occurs when incoming messages can't be deserialized.

events.name: paymentrequest
events.description: The paymentrequest event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired on a payment app when a payment flow has been initiated on the merchant website via the PaymentRequest.show() method.

events.name: periodicsync
events.description: The periodicsync event of the ServiceWorkerGlobalScope interface is fired at timed intervals, specified when registering a PeriodicSyncManager.

events.name: updatefound
events.description: The updatefound event of the ServiceWorkerRegistration interface is fired any time the ServiceWorkerRegistration.installing property acquires a new service worker.

events.name: connect

events.name: abort
events.description: The abort event of the SourceBuffer interface is fired when the buffer appending is aborted, because the SourceBuffer.abort() or SourceBuffer.remove() method is called while the SourceBuffer.appendBuffer() algorithm is still running. The updating property transitions from true to false. This event is fired before the updateend event.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event of the SourceBuffer interface is fired when an error occurs during the processing of an appendBuffer() operation. This may happen, for example, if the data being appended is not in the expected format, the SourceBuffer is in an invalid state, or the user agent is unable to process the data. The updating property transitions from true to false. This event is fired before the updateend event.

events.name: update
events.description: The update event of the SourceBuffer interface signals the successful completion of an appendBuffer() or remove() operation. The updating attribute transitions from true to false. This event is fired before the updateend event.

events.name: updateend
events.description: The updateend event of the SourceBuffer interface signals the (not necessarily successful) completion of an appendBuffer() or remove() operation. The updating attribute transitions from true to false. This event is fired after the update, error, or abort events.

events.name: updatestart
events.description: The updatestart event of the SourceBuffer interface signals the beginning of an appendBuffer() or remove() operation. The updating attribute transitions from false to true.

events.name: result
events.description: The result event of the Web Speech API is fired when the speech recognition service returns a result — a word or phrase has been positively recognized and this has been communicated back to the app

events.name: error
events.description: The error event of the Web Speech API SpeechRecognition object is fired when a speech recognition error occurs.

events.name: speechend
events.description: The speechend event of the Web Speech API is fired when speech recognized by the speech recognition service has stopped being detected.

events.name: end
events.description: The end event of the Web Speech API SpeechRecognition object is fired when the speech recognition service has disconnected.

events.name: audioend
events.description: The audioend event of the Web Speech API is fired when the user agent has finished capturing audio for speech recognition.

events.name: audiostart
events.description: The audiostart event of the Web Speech API is fired when the user agent has started to capture audio for speech recognition.

events.name: nomatch
events.description: The nomatch event of the Web Speech API is fired when the speech recognition service returns a final result with no significant recognition.

events.name: soundend
events.description: The soundend event of the Web Speech API is fired when any sound — recognizable speech or not — has stopped being detected.

events.name: soundstart
events.description: The soundstart event of the Web Speech API is fired when any sound — recognizable speech or not — has been detected.

events.name: speechstart
events.description: The speechstart event of the Web Speech API is fired when sound recognized by the speech recognition service as speech has been detected.

events.name: start
events.description: The start event of the Web Speech API SpeechRecognition object is fired when the speech recognition service has begun listening to incoming audio with intent to recognize grammars associated with the current SpeechRecognition.

events.name: voiceschanged
events.description: The voiceschanged event of the Web Speech API is fired when the list of SpeechSynthesisVoice objects that would be returned by the SpeechSynthesis.getVoices() method has changed (when the voiceschanged event fires.)

events.name: boundary
events.description: The boundary event of the Web Speech API is fired when the spoken utterance reaches a word or sentence boundary.

events.name: end
events.description: The end event of the Web Speech API SpeechSynthesisUtterance object is fired when the utterance has finished being spoken.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event of the Web Speech API SpeechSynthesisUtterance object is fired when an error occurs that prevents the utterance from being successfully spoken.

events.name: mark
events.description: The mark event of the Web Speech API SpeechSynthesisUtterance object is fired when the spoken utterance reaches a named SSML "mark" tag.

events.name: pause
events.description: The pause event of the Web Speech API SpeechSynthesisUtterance object is fired when the utterance is paused part way through.

events.name: resume
events.description: The resume event of the Web Speech API SpeechSynthesisUtterance object is fired when a paused utterance is resumed.

events.name: start
events.description: The start event of the Web Speech API SpeechSynthesisUtterance object is fired when the utterance has begun to be spoken.

events.name: paste
events.description: The paste event of the Clipboard API is fired when the user has initiated a "paste" action through the browser's user interface.

events.name: pointerdown
events.description: The pointerdown event is fired when a pointer becomes active. For mouse, it is fired when the device transitions from no buttons pressed to at least one button pressed. For touch, it is fired when physical contact is made with the digitizer. For pen, it is fired when the stylus makes physical contact with the digitizer.

events.name: transitionend
events.description: The transitionend event is fired when a CSS transition has completed. In the case where a transition is removed before completion, such as if the transition-property is removed or display is set to none, then the event will not be generated.

events.name: animationend
events.description: The animationend event is fired when a CSS Animation has completed. If the animation aborts before reaching completion, such as if the element is removed from the DOM or the animation is removed from the element, the animationend event is not fired.

events.name: copy
events.description: The copy event of the Clipboard API fires when the user initiates a copy action through the browser's user interface.

events.name: pointermove
events.description: The pointermove event is fired when a pointer changes coordinates, and the pointer has not been canceled by a browser touch-action. It's very similar to the mousemove event, but with more features.

events.name: pointerup
events.description: The pointerup event is fired when a pointer is no longer active. Remember that it is possible to get a pointercancel event instead.

events.name: pointerenter
events.description: The pointerenter event fires when a pointing device is moved into the hit test boundaries of an element or one of its descendants, including as a result of a pointerdown event from a device that does not support hover (see pointerdown). Otherwise, pointerenter works the same as mouseenter, and are dispatched at the same time. They are also dispatched at the same time as mouseover and pointerover events, if appropriate.

events.name: pointercancel
events.description: The pointercancel event is fired when the browser determines that there are unlikely to be any more pointer events, or if after the pointerdown event is fired, the pointer is then used to manipulate the viewport by panning, zooming, or scrolling.

events.name: pointerover
events.description: The pointerover event is fired when a pointing device is moved into an element's hit test boundaries.

events.name: animationstart
events.description: The animationstart event is fired when a CSS Animation has started. If there is an animation-delay, this event will fire once the delay period has expired. A negative delay will cause the event to fire with an elapsedTime equal to the absolute value of the delay (and, correspondingly, the animation will begin playing at that time index into the sequence).

events.name: selectstart
events.description: The selectstart event of the Selection API is fired when a user starts a new selection.

events.name: pointerleave
events.description: The pointerleave event is fired when a pointing device is moved out of the hit test boundaries of an element. For pen devices, this event is fired when the stylus leaves the hover range detectable by the digitizer. Otherwise, pointerleave works the same as mouseleave, and are dispatched at the same time. They are also dispatched at the same time as mouseout and pointerout events, if appropriate.

events.name: transitionstart
events.description: The transitionstart event is fired when a CSS transition has actually started, i.e., after any transition-delay has ended.

events.name: pointerout
events.description: The pointerout event is fired for several reasons including: pointing device is moved out of the hit test boundaries of an element; firing the pointerup event for a device that does not support hover (see pointerup); after firing the pointercancel event (see pointercancel); when a pen stylus leaves the hover range detectable by the digitizer.

events.name: animationiteration
events.description: The animationiteration event is fired when an iteration of a CSS Animation ends, and another one begins. This event does not occur at the same time as the animationend event, and therefore does not occur for animations with an animation-iteration-count of one.

events.name: transitionrun
events.description: The transitionrun event is fired when a CSS transition is first created, i.e., before any transition-delay has begun.

events.name: pointerrawupdate
events.description: The pointerrawupdate event is fired when a pointer changes any properties that don't fire pointerdown or pointerup events. See pointermove for a list of these properties.

events.name: lostpointercapture
events.description: The lostpointercapture event is fired when a captured pointer is released.

events.name: cut
events.description: The cut event of the Clipboard API is fired when the user has initiated a "cut" action through the browser's user interface.

events.name: animationcancel
events.description: The animationcancel event is fired when a CSS Animation unexpectedly aborts. In other words, any time it stops running without sending an animationend event. This might happen when the animation-name is changed such that the animation is removed, or when the animating node is hidden using CSS. Therefore, either directly or because any of its containing nodes are hidden.

events.name: gotpointercapture
events.description: The gotpointercapture event is fired when an element captures a pointer using setPointerCapture().

events.name: transitioncancel
events.description: The transitioncancel event is fired when a CSS transition is canceled.

events.name: beforexrselect
events.description: The beforexrselect event is fired before WebXR select events (select, selectstart, selectend) are dispatched. It can be used to suppress XR world input events while the user is interacting with a DOM overlay UI.

events.description: The online event of the Window interface is fired when the browser has gained access to the network and the value of Navigator.onLine switches to true.

events.name: beforeprint
events.description: The beforeprint event is fired when the associated document is about to be printed or previewed for printing.

events.name: focus
events.description: The focus event fires when an element has received focus.

events.name: afterprint
events.description: The afterprint event is fired after the associated document has started printing or the print preview has been closed.

events.name: offline
events.description: The offline event of the Window interface is fired when the browser has lost access to the network and the value of Navigator.onLine switches to false.

events.name: blur

events.name: deviceorientation
events.description: The deviceorientation event is fired when fresh data is available from an orientation sensor about the current orientation of the device as compared to the Earth coordinate frame. This data is gathered from a magnetometer inside the device.

events.name: orientationchange
events.description: The orientationchange event is fired when the orientation of the device has changed.

events.name: pageswap
events.description: The pageswap event is fired when you navigate across documents, when the previous document is about to unload.

events.name: pagereveal
events.description: The pagereveal event is fired when a document is first rendered, either when loading a fresh document from the network or activating a document (either from back/forward cache (bfcache) or prerender).

events.name: devicemotion
events.description: The devicemotion event is fired at a regular interval and indicates the acceleration rate of the device with/without the contribution of the gravity force at that time. It also provides information about the rate of rotation, if available.

events.name: appinstalled
events.description: The appinstalled event of the Web Manifest API is fired when the browser has successfully installed a page as an application.

events.name: languagechange
events.description: The languagechange event is fired at the global scope object when the user's preferred language changes.

events.name: gamepadconnected
events.description: The gamepadconnected event is fired when the browser detects that a gamepad has been connected or the first time a button/axis of the gamepad is used.

events.name: messageerror
events.description: The messageerror event is fired on a Window object when it receives a message that can't be deserialized.

events.name: deviceorientationabsolute
events.description: The deviceorientationabsolute event is fired when absolute device orientation changes.

events.name: rejectionhandled
events.description: The rejectionhandled event is sent to the script's global scope (usually window but also Worker) whenever a rejected JavaScript Promise is handled late, i.e., when a handler is attached to the promise after its rejection had caused an unhandledrejection event.

events.name: gamepaddisconnected
events.description: The gamepaddisconnected event is fired when the browser detects that a gamepad has been disconnected.

events.name: geometrychange
events.description: The geometrychange event is fired when the position, size, or visibility of a Progressive Web App's title bar area changes.

events.name: message
events.description: The message event is fired on a Worker object when the worker's parent receives a message from its worker (i.e., when the worker sends a message using DedicatedWorkerGlobalScope.postMessage()).

events.name: error
events.description: The error event of the Worker interface fires when an error occurs in the worker.

events.name: languagechange

events.name: offline

events.name: online

events.name: securitypolicyviolation
events.description: The securitypolicyviolation event is fired when a Content Security Policy is violated in a worker.

events.name: unhandledrejection
events.description: The unhandledrejection event is sent to the global scope (typically WorkerGlobalScope) of a script when a Promise that has no rejection handler is rejected.

events.name: readystatechange
events.description: The readystatechange event is fired whenever the readyState property of the XMLHttpRequest changes.

events.name: error
events.description: The error event is fired when the request encountered an error.

events.name: progress
events.description: The progress event is fired periodically when a request receives more data.

events.name: load
events.description: The load event is fired when an XMLHttpRequest transaction completes successfully.

events.name: loadend
events.description: The loadend event is fired when a request has completed, whether successfully (after load) or unsuccessfully (after abort or error).

events.name: loadstart
events.description: The loadstart event is fired when a request has started to load data.

events.name: timeout
events.description: The timeout event is fired when progression is terminated due to preset time expiring.

events.name: abort

events.name: redraw
events.description: The redraw event is sent to the XRCubeLayer object when the underlying resources of the layer are lost or when the XR Compositor can no longer reproject the layer. If this event is sent, authors should redraw the content of the layer in the next XR animation frame.

events.name: redraw
events.description: The redraw event is sent to the XRCylinderLayer object when the underlying resources of the layer are lost or when the XR Compositor can no longer reproject the layer. If this event is sent, authors should redraw the content of the layer in the next XR animation frame.

events.name: redraw
events.description: The redraw event is sent to the XREquirectLayer object when the underlying resources of the layer are lost or when the XR Compositor can no longer reproject the layer. If this event is sent, authors should redraw the content of the layer in the next XR animation frame.

events.name: reflectionchange
events.description: The WebXR reflectionchange event fires each time the estimated reflection cube map changes. This happens in response to use movements through different lighting conditions or to direct changes to lighting itself. This event is not cancelable.

events.name: redraw
events.description: The redraw event is sent to the XRQuadLayer object when the underlying resources of the layer are lost or when the XR Compositor can no longer reproject the layer. If this event is sent, authors should redraw the content of the layer in the next XR animation frame.

events.name: reset
events.description: The reset event is sent to an XRReferenceSpace object when a discontinuity is detected in either the native origin or the effective origin, causing a jump in the position or orientation of objects oriented using the reference space. This is common when the user calibrates or recalibrates an XR device, or if the device automatically changes its origin after losing tracking of the user, then re-gaining it.

events.name: end
events.description: An end event is fired at an XRSession object when the WebXR session has ended, either because the web application has chosen to stop the session, or because the user agent terminated the session.

events.name: inputsourceschange
events.description: The inputsourceschange event is sent to an XRSession when the set of available WebXR input devices changes.

events.name: select
events.description: The WebXR select event is sent to an XRSession when one of the session's input sources has completed a primary action.

events.name: selectend
events.description: The WebXR event selectend is sent to an XRSession when one of its input sources ends its primary action or when an input source that's in the process of handling an ongoing primary action is disconnected without successfully completing the action.

events.name: selectstart
events.description: The WebXR selectstart event is sent to an XRSession when the user begins a primary action on one of its input sources.

events.name: squeeze
events.description: The WebXR squeeze event is sent to an XRSession when one of the session's input sources has completed a primary squeeze action. Examples of common kinds of primary action are users pressing triggers or buttons, tapping a touchpad, speaking a command, or performing a recognizable gesture when using a video tracking system or handheld controller with an accelerometer.

events.name: squeezeend
events.description: The WebXR event squeezeend is sent to an XRSession when one of its input sources ends its primary action or when an input source that's in the process of handling an ongoing primary action is disconnected without successfully completing the action.

events.name: squeezestart
events.description: The WebXR event squeezestart is sent to an XRSession when the user begins a primary squeeze action on one of its input sources.

events.name: visibilitychange
events.description: The visibilitychange event is sent to an XRSession to inform it when it becomes visible or hidden, or when it becomes visible but not currently focused. Upon receiving the event, you can check the value of the session's visibilityState property to determine the new visibility state.

events.name: devicechange
events.description: A devicechange event is fired on an XRSystem object whenever the availability of immersive XR devices has changed; for example, a VR headset or AR goggles have been connected or disconnected. It's a generic Event with no added properties.
